<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 80 prisoners on a weeklong hunger strike were badly beaten by guards at 
Cuba's biggest jail last week, human rights activists said in Havana. The 
incident at the Combinado del Este jail, on the eastern outskirts of Havana, 
pitted guards armed with truncheons and steel bars against inmates jailed for 
attempting to leave the country illegally, according to a letter distributed by 
the activists to foreign reporters. The inmates were seeking 
prisoner-of-conscience status and the right to receive mail and to have regular 
family visits, among other demands, the letter said. Government officials were 
not available for comment, but they routinely refuse to answer queries on such 
matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
