</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A state-owned West German steel firm said it has evidence that blueprints 
supplied by its subsidiary for a chemical factory in Hong Kong may have been 
sent to Libya to help build a reported poison gas plant there. The company, 
Salzgitter AG, and the Finance Ministry in Bonn said in separate statements 
that a probe of the Salzgitter subsidiary uncovered a reference to Rabta, 
Libya, in a 1985 letter from Imhausen-Chemie. Imhausen is already under 
criminal investigation for its allegedly pivotal role in constructing the plant 
near Tripoli. "Salzgitter Industriebau, subcontracted by Imhausen-Chemie . . . 
was obviously deceived" about the location of the planned plant, Salzgitter 
said. 
</P>
