<P>
HONDURAS GETS 12 U.S. JETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States has delivered the last of 12 supersonic jet fighters to 
Honduras -- a move that Nicaragua views as threatening the military balance in 
Central America, military sources said. Honduras says the F-5 jets, costing a 
total of $75 million, will maintain its traditional air supremacy in the region 
and replace a fleet of aging, French-built Mirage fighters. However, Nicaraguan 
President Daniel Ortega has said his country would be justified in obtaining 
Soviet MIG-21 fighters to counteract the F-5s. Meanwhile, about 600 U.S. troops 
from Ft. Bragg, N.C., have begun a four-week exercise with Honduran troops near 
the Honduran town of La Paz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- MILITARY AID -- HONDURAS; MILITARY AIRPLANES; CENTRAL AMERICAN 
PEACE; UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- NICARAGUA; HONDURAS -- FOREIGN 
RELATIONS -- NICARAGUA; THREATS; HONDURAS -- ARMED FORCES; MILITARY MANEUVERS; 
UNITED STATES -- ARMED FORCES -- HONDURAS; NICARAGUA -- MILITARY AID -- USSR 
</P>
