<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The State Department condemned free-lance missions into Laos, saying such 
forays "are counterproductive to efforts to fully account for Americans missing 
in action." State Department spokesman Charles Redman's statement was a 
response to a protest by the Laotian government about an incursion from 
Thailand in early January, apparently involving one or two Americans. U.S. 
officials could not identify the Americans and said they did not know if they 
had been arrested. Two Americans were held by Laos last fall after crossing the 
border and spreading notices of a reward for delivery of American prisoners 
from the Vietnam War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
