Photo, A New Day Dawning for Upper Bay Children from Rose Drive Elementary 
School in Yorba Linda listen to a lecture on the Upper Newport Bay Ecological 
Reserve while looking at the estuary. A plaque on the Upper Bay is at right. 
The state Fish and Game Department has announced that under the California 
Wildlands program, the Upper Bay will be enhanced with construction of a kiosk 
and photographic blinds, a docent program for tours, direction signs, 
restrooms, improved parking areas, self-guided hiking trails, a reference 
library and specimen collection and a full-time interpreter to coordinate 
educational activities. Daily fees and annual passes will be available for 
visitors, but they are not mandatory. Fees will be used to ensure that the area 
remains a thriving ecosystem for fish and wildlife, state officials said. 
