<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two different groups of Japanese art lovers/investors are bidding on the house 
where Vincent van Gogh was born. They want to transform the building, now a 
real estate agent's office, into a museum dedicated to the Dutch painter. Van 
Gogh, who was born in 1853, spent his childhood in the house in the small 
southwestern village of Zundert in the Netherlands, but is not believed to have 
worked there. One of the groups is bidding for the property with a Belgian 
businessman, who has already bought a house in the southern French village of 
Auvers-sur-Oise where Van Gogh committed suicide in 1890. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
