<HEADLINE>
<P>
OJAI VALLEY INN LANDS SENIORS' TOURNAMENT SPURNED BY LOCAL CLUBS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH TOSCHES, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The GTE West Senior Golf Classic, blown off the Wood Ranch Country Club in Simi 
Valley by 2 years of ego-flattening winds, has landed at the Ojai Valley Inn 
and Country Club in Ventura County and will be played Dec. 1-3, tournament 
officials have announced. 
</P>
<P>
The new site of the event is 30 miles east of Santa Barbara and just a mile 
from Lake Casitas. 
</P>
<P>
The course -- built in the 1920s -- was designed by Billy Bell and George C. 
Thomas Jr., the same architects who designed Riviera Country Club, Bel-Air 
Country Club and Los Angeles Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
The tournament, which has attracted the top seniors players, including Arnold 
Palmer, Billy Casper, Chi Chi Rodriguez and Gary Player, was played at Wood 
Ranch the past 2 years. But the powerful winds that often rake the Simi Valley 
layout caused many players to complain about the course. 
</P>
<P>
Tournament officials offered the event to 2 other Valley-area country clubs -- 
North Ranch in Thousand Oaks and Lakeside in North Hollywood -- but the boards 
of directors at those clubs rejected the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
The new winter tournament is expected to have a field of 72 senior golfers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
